London Arthur Anneslay
th
Sr. I have not answered yd of 21: pass for want of occasion I am forry you
die not finde our sale to content, whoever I did the best & thought the
proffitt was little, do exspect more hence forward, because I am gott ints
the trade & that com. is become in good repatation for ittsrising which
other wise, or before was not to butt brought almost quite downs: whereforn
in case you will soe pleased to imploy butt £400 a £500: in the sulf
trade I'll add as much to itt to be equally concerned, & in case then
I can not make itt worth you will naver beleave mee more yd last
2 bales were good ware & thought they have suffered extrancgantcharges
bij comming up to london &c yett are sold to reasonable proffitt: I hope
the whites from m. Ledgingham are much forwarded inclosed a bill for
£94:16:3: on Benramin shatd att 35:7 for which please to procure
the needfull & pass to yd acctt. I have kept this mony in hopes theex
would full sudduinlys butt itt keep up rather, so shall remitt what mony
more there is for yd in cash & remaine with kinde saluts
London Will kewen
In Antwerp 29 churse
th
S in answer to yd of 11: curitt referre you to mine of 22 ditto hopeing the
packett of lace safe to yd handes bij this time, & that you shall finde them
well, for they are pure good goods as can be had, for mony inclosed the
perfect invoyce for yds governe, —I exspect to heare off itts arrivall haveing
an other packett ready to send forward next week I see what you brought
for our acctt. I exspected you should have had somd of £ 23:6 whoever
he will have itt as itt is in dying of the goods must be taken not iie
that they are not spotted as of lace many have been, the browner the
modecoleurs be the better for browne red is most demanded you may
freely fend 50 browne long cloth & 70 salempores not dyed, so as you
brought them & lett what is ready besent forward, either white or dyed
andas I noted 50 or b0 salempores in one bale of 6 demy cottons & no more
& the cottons tred with stronge ropes that they do not loose and rather
3 ropes and eachside then butt 2 of what passes exspect yd advise, becaused all
our dyed culs are gou almost butt the in carnats which do not go oftist
yd bill I have acceptes & so with hindesalut
London Henry Collier
In Antwarp 29 march 81
th th
S in answer to yd of 4 & 14 curitt am gladd you finde all my acctt. riaht
so wee will proceed in conforitie: I Button hath accepted yd bill & I ud
of the like some with £100: drawne by LK & the £35:17:10 all for
yd acctt. all the bale h 36 is sold to good proffitt, and exspect tis day N.37
of which most are sold by the pattarnes, so that I beleave shall itt them
off all very speedly, & send pattarnes for an other small bale, which I finde
will keep as out of restants a governo -
as for DH now
wee have sentence against him he not haveing opposed the law, butt by delar
of beeng out off towne so that now wee proceed to procure sent ence up on
his person or goods to gett satisfaction by selling them, or arresting hin
butt I doubt neither will take, for he keeps him self up on his countrey
house & seldon comes to towne, besides what causes more scrvple is, that he
hath transported all the estate to his soom, butt can be brought in question
because he is a live & indebted: John bichley hath shipt off a s mall pack
of tykes aboard adriaen de coninck, if they intend to send you, that I know
not yoing tom. is likely to be a captain of a comp. foot, & thus trade
& no y mony att anend, what I Bick: shall do is in cortain, herrems
doth all he can whilst I could wish with all my heart you had some thiang &
was satisfied, tis petty you suffered TH to eave england last vouge, before
you was satisfied, for thea he should have made shilst to pay to be
cleared, where now, wee rimrisico & to so with kind salute
ondon George Cole
In Antwerp 24 march
g8
th
S. in answer to yd of 25 past & 14: curitte as to the bill you speake of Jian
nott finde out in whoes handes itt shoulde be, you should have ginon a note by
the indorsment, that for non acceptance itt should be presented to mee, whoever
shall endeavour to take eare for yd konour, as well for accepting as raying
if must be what further shall pass about the same shall advise you I have
some mony ready for theestate of JS. which you may exspect p fust
whilst pro imtrem supose you finding all my acctt. right you will send
yd approbation & so renaine a word in answer concerning the lerges &
att aoon how the 22 yd moden gray es
& 24 yd ditto ale the hest ort
London Abram viians
In Antwarp 29 march
S. my last to you was on the 18: curitt sence recd. yd of 4 & 11 ditto as for the lace
trade I have now ready the newsmall flowers & some hiped ground & the nw patt
that I ordered to be finished are raddy so shall send one packett next week, which
doubt less will turne to good acctt & sett off the rest, for itt is a most curious
assortment & I am well nought assured that no man in this countrey can buy
them cheaper, for I am persuaded to be on theright butt om of that com
of which the next paclett will shew you the truth I doubt not butt N. 12 ibwi th
you before now as also the linnen which cont. a 25 att 32: butt is very good so
cost ƒ40:- now as to our trade all the goods from nelson are come to hand
N. 24 proves indifferent, because many of them do not hold out their measare
in lenght nor breath which is agreat fault, for onles the cloathes be 1½
yd broath without the list, they mustlye by & severall are ¼ of an ellled
so that must be avoyded for the future, most part of all the goods areseld
as well cloth as bayes & monyes como in, so wee must goto a fresh ordere
butt I do not know whom to imploy, ime thincks he that bought the
bale N. 29„ will do well for those cloathes prove better then the pattar
did promise, and in case you do iudge him able, wee will stick to him
for itt is best to have butt one man that undestands him self well pr
write to him to provide some draps culloured cloathes of all sorts
from 3 st ayd to 5 st ayd raw, whilst my next will bring you an
in struction & ordes for 150 cloathes: intrim lett him also buy 100 bayes
from 35: a 36 st a p to 45st ap & that as soone as he can meett penny
worths. for our demand is so quich & proffitt accordingly, that wee
shall be very siddemly out off all assortment, I hope the bale N.131-
is shipt or which cxsep exspect yd advise as also to know how northres
